## Capability

Authorize an individual Clawq principal with the same GitHub App used by P19 so
Clawq can perform explicitly requested GitHub actions as that GitHub user. The
result must preserve the real GitHub actor, be limited by both the user and App,
and never let one participant in a shared Room inherit another participants
credential.

This is an additive attribution and least-privilege enhancement for P19/P20. P19
may still operate through the App identity where policy permits; I059 is not a
hidden prerequisite for basic routing or bot-attributed actions.

## Locked architecture decisions

### Use GitHub App user access tokens

Use GitHub App user-to-server access tokens, not a separate OAuth App and not a
shared PAT.

- Browser-capable Room/web flows use the GitHub App web authorization flow.
- CLI, headless, or inaccessible-callback contexts may use GitHub Apps device
  flow when device flow is enabled for the App.
- Every flow is a resumable, expiring transaction bound to the initiating Clawq
  principal, Connector/tenant identity, source Room or Session, one-time state,
  and intended GitHub account.
- OAuth authorization proves GitHub identity and grants a token; it does not
  satisfy Clawq confirmation for a high-risk action.

GitHub App user tokens do not use traditional OAuth scopes: the returned scope is
empty and effective authority is the intersection of the users GitHub
permissions, the Apps approved permissions, the installation repository
selection, organization policy, and SSO state. Permission upgrades therefore
follow GitHub App permission/install approval and reauthorization, not arbitrary
runtime scope escalation.

### Stable principal and account binding

Persist a first-class binding:

- stable Clawq principal ID;
- Connector plus tenant/workspace plus immutable Connector user ID provenance;
- GitHub numeric user ID as the canonical identity, with login/avatar as mutable
  display metadata;
- GitHub App ID, authorization status, timestamps, and encrypted credential
  reference;
- optional user-selected default when the principal has multiple GitHub accounts.

Bindings belong to a principal, never a Room Session. Each action resolves the
current message actor and exact binding. Shared-Room history, card actions,
background completion, retries, and another participant must never reuse the
initiators token accidentally. Account ambiguity requires explicit selection.

Changing Connector display names or GitHub logins does not change identity.
Linking the same GitHub account to a second Clawq principal is rejected by
default and requires an audited admin policy exception.

### Mutable encrypted token vault

Extend the credential boundary with a mutable, encrypted, per-principal GitHub
user-token record containing access token, refresh token when issued, access and
refresh expiry, App/client identity, GitHub numeric user ID, token generation,
and last refresh/revocation status.

- Only an opaque handle/reference enters access snapshots, receipts, jobs, or
  audit records.
- Raw tokens never enter config JSON, prompts, Session history, Connector
  messages, logs, ordinary SQLite columns, tool arguments/results, worktrees, or
  runner environments.
- Refresh uses single-flight rotation with compare-and-swap generation so
  concurrent actions cannot overwrite a newly rotated refresh token.
- Expiring user tokens are required when the App supports them. Treat the normal
  eight-hour access and six-month refresh lifetimes as server-returned values,
  not hardcoded invariants.
- Expired/revoked refresh, revoked App authorization, account mismatch, encryption
  failure, and malformed responses fail closed and require relink/repair.
- Unlink revokes remotely when possible, immediately disables the local binding,
  destroys local secrets, invalidates leases/jobs, and records a redacted audit
  receipt.

The existing config-backed credential_handle/lease path should be reused for
authorization semantics, but it needs a provider capable of atomic mutable
encrypted records rather than storing rotating tokens in static config.

### Per-action auth selection

Add an explicit GitHub attribution requirement to each operation:

- App: service/bot attribution is required or explicitly chosen.
- User_required: refuse unless the current actor has a valid authorized binding.
- User_preferred: use the current actors token when valid; App fallback is allowed
  only when the action policy explicitly permits it and the preview names the
  resulting actor.

Reads remain App-first unless user context is necessary. User-attributed writes
must never silently fall back to App/PAT. Immediately before dispatch, intersect:

1. current Room/Session tool and repository capability;
2. current Clawq actor and action confirmation;
3. current GitHub user binding and token generation;
4. current App installation/repository selection and permissions;
5. current GitHub user/organization/SSO authorization; and
6. action-specific live state such as head SHA or branch protection.

An OAuth authorization is not transferable to ambient automation. Background
work may retain only an actor/binding reference and confirmation receipt; it
leases the token at the GitHub API boundary and does not expose it to external
runners. Any future authenticated Git transport requires a separate narrow
credential-broker design.

## User and admin experience

- Link, status, list accounts, choose default, relink, and unlink are available
  from the agent and CLI.
- Linking started in a Room returns to that initiating principal without posting
  secrets or reusable codes to the Room.
- Status shows GitHub login/ID, App, authorization health, SSO/permission repair
  hints, expiry class, and last successful validation, never tokens.
- Before a user-attributed mutation, preview shows repository/item, operation,
  selected GitHub account, expected GitHub actor, attribution mode, and whether
  separate action confirmation is required.
- SAML-protected organization failures explain that the user may need an active
  SSO session followed by reauthorization.
- Removing a user from a Connector/tenant, revoking their Clawq principal, or
  unlinking GitHub makes new leases fail immediately.

## Feasibility and current Clawq seams

Reusable foundations already exist:

- P19 typed plan-confirm-apply and callback setup transactions;
- P19 live GitHub App installation/repository scope;
- P19 Room-scoped tools, action policy, receipts, and high-risk confirmation;
- credential handles, access snapshots, encrypted secret resolution, and
  credential leases; and
- Github_api.resolve_github_auth_headers as the existing centralized API auth
  seam.

Missing foundations owned by this Idea are the stable cross-Connector principal
binding, mutable encrypted rotating-token provider, GitHub user authorization
transactions, and per-action attribution-aware auth resolution.

## Candidate decomposition when promoted

1. GitHub user authorization transaction and web/device adapters.
2. Principal-to-GitHub-account binding schema and link/status/unlink surfaces.
3. Atomic encrypted rotating token provider and revocation lifecycle.
4. Attribution-aware GitHub auth resolver and P19 action integration.
5. Shared-Room isolation, SSO/permission repair, audit, migration, and live pilot.

Prefer a dedicated milestone or cohesive epic after P19 foundations rather than
scattering token work through P19 action tasks.

## Acceptance contract

- Web and enabled device flows bind only the initiating principal and survive
  restart without replay or cross-Room completion.
- The returned GitHub numeric identity is verified through GitHub before binding.
- Two users in one Room can invoke the same action and GitHub attributes each to
  the correct user; an unlinked third user cannot borrow either credential.
- Effective access is constrained by Clawq policy plus user, App, installation,
  repository, organization, and SSO authorization.
- Access/refresh rotation is atomic under concurrency and refresh-token replay
  cannot roll state backward.
- Revocation, unlink, expiry, App permission changes, repository removal, SSO
  failure, and Connector identity changes fail closed with actionable repair.
- App, User_required, and User_preferred selection is deterministic and recorded
  in redacted previews, receipts, and audit.
- No raw token appears in config serialization, logs, prompts, Session history,
  Connector output, tool payloads, jobs, worktrees, runner environments, or audit
  export.
- Existing App-installation and PAT behavior remains compatible and no write-as-
  user action silently falls back to either.
- Live verification links two test principals, performs separately attributed
  writes, rotates a token, tests denial/revocation, and cleans up bindings and
  GitHub artifacts with a redacted receipt.

## Out of scope

- Using GitHub authorization as Clawqs general login/session authentication.
- A generic OAuth broker for non-GitHub services.
- Impersonation without a user-granted GitHub App token.
- Passing GitHub user tokens into coding-agent runners or arbitrary shell tools.
- Automatically approving new GitHub App permissions or organization access.

